This is the closest in accuracy yet. Worked using hdc (UK) and colour work where the the non-active thread runs inside each stitch, resulting in for more uniform tension (contrast with 

).

Consider a torus embedded in \mathbb{R}^3, centred on the origin and with major and minor radii R>r>0.



Figure 1:Diagram of a torus with radii R>r>0.

A corresponding parametrisation is\begin{gather*}
\mathbf{r}:[-\pi,\pi]\times[0,2\pi]\to\mathbb{R}^3; \hspace{1em} \mathbf{r}(\theta,\phi)=(x,y,z) \\
x=(R-r\cos\theta)\cos\phi, \hspace{1em} y=(R-r\cos\theta)\sin\phi, \hspace{1em} z=r\sin\theta
\end{gather*}

E=\mathbf{r}_\theta^2=r^2, \hspace{1em} F=\mathbf{r}_\theta\cdot\mathbf{r}_\phi=0 \hspace{1em} G=\mathbf{r}_\phi^2=(R-r\cos\theta)^2L=\mathbf{r}_{\theta\theta}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}}=-r,\hspace{1em}
M=\mathbf{r}_{\theta\phi}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}}=0, \hspace{1em} N=\mathbf{r}_{\phi\phi}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}}=(R-r\cos\theta)\cos\theta.

So, the first and second fundamental forms are\mathbf{I}=r^2d\theta^2 + (R-r\cos\theta)^2d\phi, \hspace{.5em}\text{ and }\hspace{.5em}\mathbf{II}=-r\,d\theta^2+(R-r\cos\theta)\cos\theta\,d\phi^2.

Contracting the curvature tensor according to R_{ij}=R^m_{imj} gives\begin{gather*}
R_{\theta\theta}=R^\theta_{\theta\theta\theta}+R^\phi_{\theta\phi\theta}=-\frac{1}{r}\cos\theta(R-r\cos\theta), \\
R_{\phi\phi}=R^\theta_{\phi\theta\phi}+R^\phi_{\phi\phi\phi}=-\frac{\cos\theta}{R-r\cos\theta}
\end{gather*}
